  <!-- 4.1 -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 01" label="Section 4.1" title="Sustainability in Municipal Administration" id="s-4-1">
    <p>In Switzerland, sustainability is a democratic effort driven by the 26 cantons and around 2,000 municipalities, each of which holds their own binding tools (Kammerer et al., 2023). The federal Energy Strategy 2050, locked in by referendum in 2017, sets the direction: phasing out nuclear, scaling up renewables, and capping per-capita primary energy (Notter, 2015; IEA, 2023). But most of the actual CO₂ cuts happen locally through building rules, procurement, and the way a municipality runs its own buildings.</p>
    <p>The key tool is the <em>Energiestadt</em> label — the Swiss arm of the European Energy Award — which has certified more than 460 municipalities since 1988, Oberägeri included (Trägerverein Energiestadt, 2020). The label audits six policy areas every four years and Gold requires that 75 % of measures are in place. Evaluations by the Swiss Federal Office of Energy show, even with causal-isolation difficulties, that certified municipalities make more energy- and climate-conscious decisions than non-certified ones (Iten et al., 2004). Recent literature notes that municipal sustainability work in Switzerland has so far been mostly about energy efficiency, while adaptation and integrated planning still rely on a few pioneer actors rather than institutional capacity (Desthieux &amp; Joerin, 2022).</p>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.2 -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 02" label="Section 4.2" title="Energy Efficiency in Public Buildings" id="s-4-2">
    <p>For public buildings in Switzerland, the legal framework is set by SIA 380/1, which caps annual heat demand at 16 kWh/m² for new builds and 24 kWh/m² for renovations (IEA, n.d.). This cap is written into cantonal law through the <em>Mustervorschriften der Kantone im Energiebereich</em> (MuKEn), adopted in full or in parts by all 26 cantons, Zug included (EnDK, 2018). Additional labels like Minergie are voluntary as they are typically more rigorous than the legal caps. When implemented, a Minergie retrofit can cut heating energy by around 70 % compared to a poorly insulated 1970s building (Le Guen et al., 2018).</p>
    <p>Unfortunately, buildings built before 1980 still account for around 70 % of Swiss heating-energy demand (Streicher et al., 2018). Stock-flow modelling shows the federal 2050 carbon-neutrality target only works if envelope retrofits, renewable heating and rooftop PV are implemented simultaneously (Roca-Puigròs et al., 2020). Yet the only nation-wide econometric study of Swiss retrofits found that subsidised renovations actually deliver only 10–20 % energy savings on average — well below engineering predictions (Hondeborg et al., 2023). Any project-level scenario for the Rathaus has to account for that performance gap, with envelope U-values often two to three times above current MuKEn requirements (Streicher et al., 2018).</p>
  </Section>

