  <!-- 4.4 Solar Thermal -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 04" label="Section 4.4" title="Solar Thermal Energy" id="s-4-4">
    <p><strong>Solar-thermal systems convert sunlight directly into heat</strong> used for hot water production or to supplement space heating. A typical system consists of collectors on the roof and a heat-storage tank (Han et al., 2025). According to Swissolar (2024), a solar-thermal system covers at least 30 % of annual heat demand.</p>

    <h3>Collector categories</h3>
    <p>There are two main categories of solar-thermal collectors: <strong>concentrating</strong> and <strong>non-concentrating</strong>. Concentrating collectors (parabolic troughs, compound parabolic concentrators) reach very high temperatures and are mostly used in power plants. Non-concentrating collectors (flat-plate, evacuated-tube) provide 30–100 °C, which is sufficient for hot water and space heating in buildings (Omeiza et al., 2024). For this project only non-concentrating types are relevant.</p>

    <ul class="dashed">
      <li><strong>Flat-plate collector</strong> — solar radiation strikes a black-coated absorber surface, which transfers heat to a storage tank via a heat-transfer fluid. A glass cover lets radiation pass through but prevents convective and radiative losses (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
      <li><strong>Evacuated tube collector</strong> — same principle, but the absorber is enclosed in two concentric glass tubes with a vacuum between them. The vacuum acts as effective insulation, so this collector type operates more efficiently than flat-plate even under cloudy skies and low outdoor temperatures (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advantages and disadvantages</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages</h4>
        <p>Albertí et al. (2014) show that over their lifetime, solar-thermal systems reduce GHG emissions by ≈ <strong>65 %</strong>, ozone depletion by <strong>69 %</strong>, and photochemical ozone formation by <strong>41 %</strong> compared to gas heating.</p>
        <p>Increasing the share of solar thermal in domestic hot-water production from 7.8 % to 30 % in Spain would yield <strong>1.24–1.64 Mt CO₂/yr</strong> in savings. In China the potential is even greater (≈ 0.63 % of national emissions) due to the coal-heavy mix.</p>
        <p>Solar-thermal collectors achieve an energy-conversion efficiency of <strong>up to 70 %</strong> (BBSR, 2024), versus ≈ 17 % for PV. A further benefit: in winter, operating heat melts accumulated snow on the collectors automatically (Omeiza et al., 2024).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Disadvantages</h4>
        <p><strong>Long payback.</strong> Han et al. (2025) find an average payback of <strong>50.4 years</strong>, driven by high upfront cost and the lower economic value of thermal energy. Context matters — Krawczyk et al. (2019) calculate <strong>17–19 years</strong> for public buildings with high hot-water demand.</p>
        <p><strong>Other environmental categories.</strong> Production releases pollutants contributing to acidification (6 % worse) and eutrophication (61 % worse) than conventional gas systems. The cause: copper pipes, collectors and water tanks (Albertí et al., 2019).</p>
        <p><strong>Corrosion risk.</strong> Salty atmospheres and high-temperature operation break down protective coatings and promote galvanic corrosion. Aged heat-transfer fluids can release aggressive compounds (Omeiza et al., 2024).</p>
        <p><strong>Climate dependence.</strong> Krawczyk et al. (2020) show a collector in Spain delivers three times the energy of an identical one in Poland. A backup heat source is therefore necessary in winter.</p>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.5 Photovoltaics -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 05" label="Section 4.5" title="Photovoltaics" id="s-4-5">
    <p>Photovoltaic panels (PV), or solar panels, are becoming a viable and cheap solution for transitioning to renewable energy production. PV is frequently seen on roofs, on building exteriors, or on fields creating "solar farms". PV is a sustainable way of producing energy by absorbing the photons naturally produced by the sun's rays. Most current models have rated outputs of 400–450 W and module efficiencies of 19–22 %. In optimal conditions on the Swiss plateau, a 1 kWp panel can deliver about 1,000 kWh per year.</p>

    <p>Five categories of panel are available on the market:</p>
    <ul class="dashed">
      <li><strong>Crystalline silicon cells</strong> — mono- or polycrystalline. Monocrystalline use single-crystal silicon (highly efficient, more expensive); polycrystalline are made from multiple silicon cells (less efficient, cheaper).</li>
      <li><strong>Single-junction gallium arsenide cells</strong> — among the highest efficiencies on the market, very robust, mostly used for aerospace and military.</li>
      <li><strong>Multijunction cells</strong> — several semiconductor materials capture a wider range of photons; more expensive to produce, very efficient.</li>
      <li><strong>Thin films</strong> — a thin semiconductor laid on a substrate. Three key types: amorphous silicon, cadmium telluride, and copper-indium-gallium-selenide.</li>
      <li><strong>Emerging PV</strong> — organic materials, quantum-dot cells; experimental and not yet comparable to the other four categories.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advantages and disadvantages</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages</h4>
        <p><strong>Energy efficiency.</strong> Current models reach 400–450 W and 19–22 % efficiency. In the Swiss midlands a well-placed 1 kWp system yields ~1,000 kWh/year (Swiss Solar Verband, n.d.).</p>
        <p><strong>Installation flexibility.</strong> Panels can be integrated into existing structures with minimal disruption. Multiple PV technologies allow cost &amp; performance optimisation.</p>
        <p><strong>Recycling.</strong> Switzerland has a dedicated recycling network (Sens eRecycling). Panels have a long lifetime (~25 years).</p>
        <p><strong>Environmental impact.</strong> During sun collection the energy produced is carbon-neutral and renewable. Can be installed on roofs, façades, or land.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Disadvantages</h4>
        <p><strong>Energy efficiency.</strong> Performance is highly sensitive to placement, orientation, and cleanliness. Snow, shading and debris reduce output.</p>
        <p><strong>Recycling limits.</strong> Recycling systems in Germany are lacking (El Khawad et al., 2022). Panels are not designed for reuse, repair or refurbishment. Recycling is energy-intensive, loses material value, and does not recover all components.</p>
        <p><strong>Embodied carbon.</strong> Production and recycling are not carbon-neutral — they require rare or energy-intensive materials (e.g. glass).</p>
        <p><strong>Variability.</strong> Energy production depends on sunlight availability, shading, and weather conditions.</p>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.6 Emergency Power -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 06" label="Section 4.6" title="Emergency Power Systems" id="s-4-6">
    <p>The municipality must be able to operate 24 hours a day in crisis situations, which requires an on-site generator to ensure uninterrupted power. Oberägeri currently relies on a diesel generator for emergencies, but this system is neither carbon-reducing nor carbon-neutral. Alternatives evaluated here are biofuel generators, biogas generators, and battery-powered (PV + battery) systems.</p>

    <h3>Biofuel and biogas generators</h3>
    <p>Biofuels are produced from <em>feedstock</em> — biomass sources such as wood, ethanol and biodiesel (Clarence Lehman, 2026). Because the carbon released during combustion is part of a short biological cycle, biofuels can reduce GHG emissions, although additional emissions occur during production and land-use processes.</p>
    <p>Biogas generators run on biogas produced via anaerobic digestion and offer substantially lower life-cycle GHG emissions and reduced NOₓ and smoke compared with diesel (van den Oever et al., 2021; Nayak &amp; Sahoo, 2020). One study found a solar-biogas hybrid configuration to be the most feasible, with a net present cost of <strong>$386,971</strong>, cost of energy of <strong>$0.476/kWh</strong>, and CO₂ emissions of <strong>10,346 kg/yr</strong> (Li et al., 2022). However, high annual maintenance costs (~$87,000), gas-cleaning, corrosion, and variable biogas availability make biogas systems unsuitable for Oberägeri.</p>

    <h3>Battery-powered (PV + battery) generators</h3>
    <p>Battery-powered generators rely on PV panels to produce electricity that is stored for emergency use. A properly designed PV + battery system can achieve reliability comparable to diesel (Jurasz et al., 2020; Ali et al., 2023). Long-term performance depends on solar variability, panel degradation and battery-capacity decline — requiring oversizing to maintain <strong>95 % reliability after 20 years</strong> (Jurasz et al., 2020).</p>

    <h3>Diesel generators — the incumbent baseline</h3>
    <p>Diesel generators are inexpensive to purchase but have high operating costs, a higher cost of energy, and approximately <strong>70 % higher CO₂ emissions</strong> than PV + battery alternatives (Ali et al., 2023; Felice et al., 2023). Reliability depends heavily on maintenance: well-maintained units have a <strong>20 % probability of failure within two weeks</strong>; poorly maintained units a <strong>50 % probability within the first 48 hours</strong> (Marqusee &amp; Jenket, 2020). Diesel fuel must be replaced every 6–12 months to avoid bacterial contamination (Hwang et al., 2023).</p>

    <h3>Diesel vs. PV + battery — comparison</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages of PV + battery</h4>
        <p><strong>Near-instant response.</strong> Switchover occurs within milliseconds (Synergy, 2024) — compared with diesel's typical &gt; 10 s delay (Costa et al., 2023).</p>
        <p><strong>Higher self-sufficiency.</strong> <strong>96.83 %</strong> for PV + battery vs <strong>39.15 %</strong> for diesel (Felice et al., 2023).</p>
        <p><strong>Lower emissions.</strong> Roughly <strong>70 % lower CO₂</strong>, no fuel-transport footprint, no on-site combustion.</p>
        <p><strong>Customisable design.</strong> PV array and battery sizing can be matched to the building's load and resilience targets.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Limitations of diesel generators</h4>
        <p><strong>High emissions.</strong> On-site combustion releases CO₂, NOₓ and particulates; locked into a fossil-fuel supply chain.</p>
        <p><strong>Delayed response.</strong> Start-up and synchronisation take &gt; 10 s — long enough to interrupt sensitive IT and communications equipment.</p>
        <p><strong>Fuel-degradation risks.</strong> Stored diesel must be replaced every 6–12 months to prevent contamination-induced failure.</p>
        <p><strong>Maintenance-sensitive reliability.</strong> Well-maintained units: 20 % failure probability within two weeks; poorly maintained: 50 % within 48 hours.</p>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

